{{see also|Omen}}
[[File:Gate Token.png|left|150px|link=]] Gate tokens represent tears in the fabric of reality. These gateways can lead to other worlds, dimensions, or even points in time. These dangerous anomalies allow deadly powers into our world, such as [[Monsters]] and eventually even the [[Ancient Ones]]. Gates are mostly specific to locations that have unique pictures by their name. This includes major cities like [[Rome]], or, with expansions, places where an [[Expedition Encounters|Expedition Encounter]] can take place like [[The Pyramids]] or Atlantis (space 8). {{icon|mom}}, {{icon|utp}}, and {{icon|td}} have side boards with spaces where Gates may spawn. 

All Gates have one of three symbols on them that correspond to the [[Omen]]. When the omen rotates to that symbol, {{icon|doom}} advances by 1 for each Gate that bears the symbol. Gates do NOT advance Doom when spawned, even if the Omen corresponds with that Gate.

__TOC__

The Gate stack is created by randomizing all the Gate tokens, including those for a Side Board if playing with them, then placing them facedown. Gates are kept facedown in the Gate stack until they are spawned, unless an ability allows an investigator to look at them.

It's rare, but possible, to have multiple Gates on the same space. In this case, during the Encounter Phase, an investigator on that space may choose one of the Gates to encounter.{{Ref|bgg=thread/1703514/article/25946201|name=Multiple Gates on the same space}}

===Spawning Gates===
[[File:Spawn Gates.png|left|56px|link=]] When an effect spawns a Gate, draw one Gate token from the top of the Gate stack and place it faceup on the space indicated on the Gate token. When a Gate is spawned, a [[Monster]] is spawned on the same space. Gates are most commonly opened when spawned by a [[Mythos]] card when the appropriate symbol appears on the top part of the card, always occurring on the cards with yellow backgrounds. They may also be opened through certain [[Rumor]] Mythos cards, through a failed [[Encounter]], or some condition effects.

When there are no Gates remaining in the Gate stack, place all discarded Gates facedown in the Gate stack and randomize them. If a Gate cannot be spawn because the Gate stack and discard pile are empty, advance {{icon|doom}} by 1 instead.

===Closing Gates===
[[File:Other World Encounter.png|thumb|right|120px|Back of an Other World Encounter]]{{main|Other World Encounters}}
During the Encounter Phase, an investigator on a space containing a Gate may encounter it by drawing and resolving an [[Other World Encounter]]. Many Other World Encounters result in allowing the player to "close" the Gate. If this happens, the Gate token is removed from the board and put into a discard pile.

Some effects, such as a [[Mystic Ruins Encounter]], may allow an investigator to "discard" a gate from the game board. This follows the same process but is not considered "closing" the gate.{{Ref|faq=10|name=faq10}}

===Revealing Gates===
When an effect reveals a Gate, change one Gate token from the top of the Gate stack to a faceup position. Revealed Gates remain where they are in the Gate stack unless the effect that causes the Gates to be revealed states otherwise.

If an effect would cause a number of Gates to be revealed that exceeds the number of Gates in the Gate stack, the active [[investigator]] randomizes the Gates in the discard pile and places them at the bottom of the Gate stack before resolving that effect.

After a Gate in the Gate stack has been revealed, it remains revealed until it is removed from the Gate stack or the Gate stack is randomized.<ref name=faq10 />

Revealing a Gate that has previously been revealed has no additional effect. This won't stop other effects from manipulating those Gates; for instance, [[Randolph Carter]] will be able to put the top Gate on the bottom of the Gate stack if desired, even if the top Gate has already been revealed by some other effects.{{Ref|bgg=thread/1724129/article/25153704|name=Revealed Gates}}

